		<div>
			<h4>Grading</h4>
			<div>
				<h5>Attendance</h5>
				<p>Coming to class is very important. For this reason, and to learn your name, I will take attendance every class. If you cannot make it to class, please let me know beforehand. Even if you are confused, come to class. Confusion is a part of the learning, especially with a subject like math. If you are lost, get in touch with me or drop into one of the <a href="#tutoring">tutoring labs</a>. There are many resources on campus to help you through this class.</p>
			</div>
			<div>
				<h5>Homework</h5>
				<div id="gradeScale">
					<table>
						<thead>
							<tr>
								<th scope="col">Grade</th>
								<th scope="col">Cutoffs</th>
							</tr>
						</thead>
						<tbody>
							<tr><th scope="row">A</th><td>90&ndash;100%</td></tr>
							<tr><th scope="row">B</th><td>80&ndash;89%</td></tr>
							<tr><th scope="row">C</th><td>70&ndash;79%</td></tr>
							<tr><th scope="row">D</th><td>60&ndash;69%</td></tr>
							<tr><th scope="row">F</th><td>0&ndash;59%</td></tr>
						</tbody>
						<caption>Grade Scale</caption>
					</table>
				</div>
				<p>Homework is where you practice the skills with the new techniques and shape your understanding of the new ideas. I try to have reasonable assignments and due dates. In return, I expect that you will turn homework in on time. While I will glance over late homework for errors, I have no obligation to accept late homework. But life can get in the way of homework. So I like to drop the lowest two homework scores from each student’s grade. On each homework, put your name, my name (“Cousino”), and the course (“Math 1315”). This helps to ensure your homework ends up in my hands at the end of the day, even if it gets misplaced.</p>
				<p>Homework will be graded based upon correctness and not completeness. This is to help better prepare you for exams, which are also graded on correctness. But also, this practice helps to give you more information about what you are doing correctly and what you need more practice doing. In a following section, I explain what <a href="#showWork">showing your work</a> means to me.</p>
			</div>
			<div>
				<h5>Exams</h5>
				<div id="gradeDistribution">
					<table>
						<thead>
							<tr>
								<th scope="col">Category</th>
								<th scope="col">Weights</th>
							</tr>
						</thead>
						<tbody>
							<tr><th scope="row">Attendance</th><td>5%</td></tr>
							<tr><th scope="row">Homework</th><td>15%</td></tr>
							<tr><th scope="row">Exam 1</th><td>20%</td></tr>
							<tr><th scope="row">Exam 2</th><td>20%</td></tr>
							<tr><th scope="row">Exam 3</th><td>20%</td></tr>
							<tr><th scope="row">Final Exam</th><td>20%</td></tr>
						</tbody>
						<caption>Grade Distribution</caption>
					</table>
				</div>
				<p>There will be three mid-term exams as well as a cumulative final exam. All of the exams will consist of short answer questions, in which you are expected to <a href="#showWork">show your work</a> along with your answer. As mentioned earlier, exams will be graded for correctness and partial credit will be given. The class before each exam, we will have a review for the entire class. At the beginning of each review day, I will list out the topic of each question on the exam and tell you which homework problems are similar to that exam question. I like to announce exam days at least a week prior. Exam dates in the tentative schedule and <a href="#dates">important dates</a> are not written in stone. They are required by the state of Texas. If I feel that we need to spend more time on a topic, then I will do just that. The schedule be damned.</p>
				<p>Exams are how I assess whether you have learned the subject. The questions on my exam reflect this. I can give justifications for putting each question on every exam. With each question, I think whether it is fair to include it and how it assesses something unique from the others. Because I work hard on the exams, tell you what’s on them, and announce them in advance, I expect you to be in class to take them. If you have to miss any mid-term exam (not the final) for a justifiable reason, let me know prior so we can schedule a make-up exam. Examples of good reasons are serious illness/injury, extracurricular activities, and family emergencies; examples of bad reasons are sleeping through an exam, forgetting about an exam, and not being prepared for an exam.</p>
			</div>
			<div>
				<h5>Showing Your Work</h5>
				<p>Math is more about the process to get the answer than it is about the answer itself. My rule of thumb is that if I have to show my work, then so do you. When going through examples in class, I will note how much work is expected of you. If you ever are unclear about this, please ask me in class, outside of class, or during an exam.</p>
			</div>
		</div>
		<div>
			<h4>Technology Used for Instruction</h4>
